52
00:07:16,613 --> 00:07:18,303
had granted it by his command.

53
00:07:18,303 --> 00:07:25,684
We provide the full document elsewhere and confirm it with other imperial records and the constitution of Pope Saint Leo the Ninth.

54
00:07:25,684 --> 00:07:38,924
Saint Boniface, archbishop of Cologne, mentioned this matter in a letter to Pope Stephen, and among his letters to Serrarius, number 97, published; we provide it elsewhere and prove that it concerns Dagobert, the son of Saint Sigebert.

55
00:07:38,924 --> 00:07:44,501
Besides the son raised from death by the prayers of Saint Arbogast, Dagobert had several daughters.

56
00:07:44,501 --> 00:07:54,586
The most notable among them is Saint Irmina, a virgin and the first abbess of the monastery of Horrea near Trier, also recorded in the Roman Martyrology on December twenty-fourth.

57
00:07:55,487 --> 00:08:04,469
She was buried in the monastery of Wissembourg, generously endowed by her father Dagobert, who, as we've shown elsewhere, founded or supported many monasteries.

58
00:08:04,469 --> 00:08:08,342
Another daughter of Dagobert, and niece of Saint Sigebert, was Adela.

59
00:08:08,342 --> 00:08:15,808
Inspired by her sister Irmina's example after her husband's death, Adela also embraced a monastic lifestyle and led a very holy life.

60
00:08:15,808 --> 00:08:23,218
She became the abbess of the monastery built at Palatiolum on the Moselle River's bank and bequeathed her possessions to its church.

61
00:08:23,218 --> 00:08:29,785
Her will was signed on April first in the twelfth year of King Theodoric, specifically the last one, in the year 731.

62
00:08:29,785 --> 00:08:32,536
Her sister Regentrudis is mentioned in that will.

63
00:08:32,536 --> 00:08:42,022
Without her, some claim Rathilde, or Rothilde, was the third daughter of Dagobert and believe she married Luderic Bucanus, founder of the castle in Lille, Galloflanders.

64
00:08:42,022 --> 00:08:45,503
However, we have not yet found this proven by ancient records.

65
00:08:45,503 --> 00:08:57,291
What is certain is that Alberic, Adela's son, fathered many children, including Saint Gregory, who was a close companion of Saint Boniface until his death and later served as a priest for the bishop of Utrecht.

66
00:08:57,291 --> 00:09:00,041
Saint Ludger, his disciple, wrote about his life.

67
00:09:00,041 --> 00:09:09,977
Whether Saint Alberic, who later became bishop of Utrecht, descended from one of Saint Gregory’s brothers and was named after his grandfather, is something we explore elsewhere.

68
00:09:09,977 --> 00:09:14,356
Saint Gregory is celebrated on August 25th and Saint Alberic on November 14th.

69
00:09:14,356 --> 00:09:25,414
Whether the Saint Dagobert, venerated as a martyr among the people of Sathanacum in Lorraine, was a king of the Franks and the son of Saint Sigebert, we do not yet dare to determine with certainty.

70
00:09:26,087 --> 00:09:28,367
