71
00:09:28,367 --> 00:09:35,956
The author of the Acts of Saint Sigebert mentions that twelve monasteries were built, which Gelenius attributes solely to Ardennes.

72
00:09:35,956 --> 00:09:45,051
In total, twenty monasteries were constructed, according to Molanus in the Auctarium Usuardi, Galesinus, and Saussay, whose words we have referenced earlier.

73
00:09:45,051 --> 00:09:54,900
Brouwer, in his unpublished work Metropolis, writes about them as follows:
In the year 651, Sigebert, King of the Austrasians, was flourishing in his royal court at Metz.

74
00:09:54,900 --> 00:10:00,924
He was renowned for his remarkable innocence and outstanding generosity toward various religious orders.

75
00:10:00,924 --> 00:10:06,717
He established and expanded monasteries of significant size, enriching them with perpetual revenues.

76
00:10:06,717 --> 00:10:13,785
Among these were Malmedy and Stavelot on the borders of Ardennes, and the monastery of Saint Martin in the suburb of Metz.

77
00:10:13,785 --> 00:10:18,999
This is what Brouwer reports, but neither he nor others mention the remaining monasteries.

78
00:10:18,999 --> 00:10:22,822
We will discuss the one founded and later destroyed in Metz below.

79
00:10:22,822 --> 00:10:35,509
In the Life of Saint Amandus, celebrated on February 6, we will note that while the holy King Sigebert ruled the Austrasians, many monasteries were built in the Belgian and German provinces, which we will not list here.

80
00:10:35,509 --> 00:10:47,326
Before Stavelot and Malmedy, another monastery was erected at Chiny in the Duchy of Luxembourg by the river Sesmarum or Sesomirim, commonly called Sesmoy or Semoy, between the towns of Chiny and Bouillon.

81
00:10:47,326 --> 00:10:51,266
In later centuries, this became a priory in the district of Cougnon.

82
00:10:51,266 --> 00:10:55,784
We will discuss it in more detail on February 3, in the Life of Saint Hadelin.

83
00:10:55,784 --> 00:11:05,575
Below, in Column 319, diploma I, we provide the diploma of Saint Sigebert, shared with us by the very kind John Anthony Gournesius, a priest of the Oratory congregation.

84
00:11:05,575 --> 00:11:11,773
This confirms that Saint Remaclus was appointed abbot, even though he was not yet the bishop of Maastricht.

85
00:11:11,773 --> 00:11:19,420
The bishop of Metz, Godo, also known as Dodo or Godeo, was still alive, and the saintly Clodulf, son of Saint Arnulf, succeeded him.

86
00:11:19,420 --> 00:11:23,938
To this bishop, Remaclus sent Saint Trudo in the first year of his episcopate.

87
00:11:23,938 --> 00:11:37,089
This effectively refutes Bouchet, who, in Part I of the Origins of the Royal Family of the Franks, chapter 6, counts the episcopate of Godo from 659 to 667, and believes Saint Clodulf succeeded him and lived until the year 707.

88
00:11:38,015 --> 00:11:41,827
In the document, aside from Sesomirim, the river Alsnia is mentioned.

89
00:11:41,827 --> 00:11:48,510
It rises above Luxembourg, flows past the city, joins the Atarto, empties into the Sura, and then flows into the Moselle.

90
00:11:48,510 --> 00:11:52,210
The forest Uriacuise extends to the village of Ures below Bouillon.

91
00:11:52,210 --> 00:11:55,911
It should be read as Viracuise, referring to the nearby river Vire.

92
00:11:55,911 --> 00:11:59,114
Understanding these points will make the document clearer.

93
00:11:59,114 --> 00:12:08,559
Notgerus, Bishop of Liège, in the Life of Saint Remaclus, Bishop of Maastricht, on September 3rd, mentions another Life written by an older and nearly contemporary author.

94
00:12:08,559 --> 00:12:22,367
He writes in the prologue to Abbot Werenfrid: You offered a booklet about the Life of both our and your special patron, Lord Remaclus, lamenting that due to the negligence of your predecessors, it was shorter than the greatness of his deeds required.

95
00:12:22,367 --> 00:12:30,596
At the same time, you seemed, if I may not say begged, but rather urged, that it should be not only copied but also polished somewhat more elegantly.

96
00:12:30,596 --> 00:12:55,948
In this earlier booklet, or Life of Saint Remaclus, it is written about the monasteries built at Stavelot and Malmedy: It happened, by God's favor, that the pious rulers of the Frankish kingdom, King Sigebert and Duke Grimoald, by God's will and the advice of their nobles, ordered that monasteries be built within the forest, located in the district called Ardennes, named Stavelot and Malmedy, where religious monks would dwell and serve Christ spiritually.

97
00:12:55,948 --> 00:13:04,564
They would pray to Almighty God for the well-being of the whole kingdom, and the safety of the king and his sons, or those exercising care over the kingdom.

98
00:13:04,564 --> 00:13:12,407
Then they began to build diligently, and, as is usual in such work, divine power followed, and they were completed swiftly with great success.

99
00:13:12,959 --> 00:13:22,117
When it was time to dedicate the newly adorned church buildings, the king called upon the blessed Bishop Remaclus, because one of the churches, Stavelot, was part of his diocese.

100
00:13:22,117 --> 00:13:28,547
The other, Malmedy, fell under the jurisdiction of the metropolis, with the consent of Cunibert, the metropolitan of Cologne.

101
00:13:28,547 --> 00:13:32,303
The bishop was summoned to dedicate them in accordance with his ministry.

102
00:13:32,303 --> 00:13:39,402
The very holy man promptly obeyed and diligently carried out the task assigned to him, which had been accomplished through his leadership.

103
00:13:39,402 --> 00:13:47,325
Being close to and beloved by the king and the chief officials of the palace due to his great holiness, no important decision was made without his advice.

104
00:13:47,325 --> 00:13:59,260
Because he was so cherished by them, after the solemn celebration of the Masses, the mayor of the palace, Grimoald, entrusted these places to him, to manage everything under his authority and uphold the rules of monastic life there.

105
00:13:59,260 --> 00:14:11,658
Not long afterward, he finally obtained permission from the king, allowing him to leave a successor in the episcopal seat, as he had long desired, so he could retreat to this solitary place and devote himself solely to God, away from people.

106
00:14:11,658 --> 00:14:20,352
Thus, with vigilant care, he maintained the teachings of monastic life without reproach and inspired many noble men to adopt that way of life, which he taught perfectly.

107
00:14:20,352 --> 00:14:23,850
What he taught with words, he first ensured to fulfill with actions.

108
00:14:23,850 --> 00:14:29,612
As a result, as religion grew, the income of the church increased, benefiting the servants of God working there.

109
00:14:29,612 --> 00:14:43,553
When the aforementioned devout rulers heard of this religious practice, they summoned the blessed man and granted him twelve leagues in length and width from the forest, where no one could challenge his or his successors' authority, allowing them to serve God peacefully.

110
00:14:43,553 --> 00:14:51,322
They also confirmed this by testament with imperial seals, ensuring its permanence, which the most holy Father gladly accepted and held with reverence.

111
00:14:51,887 --> 00:14:57,747
However, not long after, he aimed to shorten the time so that it could be done more easily for the followers.

112
00:14:57,747 --> 00:15:04,520
Without any obstacles, the leaders of the place could maintain what seems to have endured completely unchanged up to our time.

113
00:15:04,520 --> 00:15:10,863
The monasteries of Stavelot and Malmedy are located nearly 8 miles from Liège, in the direction of the East and Trier.

114
00:15:10,863 --> 00:15:16,292
Both began construction around the year 655, which was the sixth year of Saint Remaclus's episcopate.

115
00:15:16,292 --> 00:15:19,840
The charters were granted towards the end of King Sigebert's life.

116
00:15:19,840 --> 00:15:23,925
Part of these charters is presented by Notger in the Life of Saint Remaclus.

117
00:15:23,925 --> 00:15:25,645
We provide these charters below.

